  "prompt": "Which country does the prime minister/president have the least power over the country?",
  "response": "In countries with a parliamentary system, the head of state (often a president or monarch) typically has less political power compared to the head of government (usually the prime minister). However, in terms of the head of government having relatively minimal power, several factors could be considered.\n\nSwitzerland is often cited as an example where the president has limited power. The Swiss president serves a one-year term and is primarily a ceremonial and collegial role within the Federal Council, which collectively acts as the executive authority. In this system, the decision-making power is distributed among seven federal councillors, minimizing the concentration of power in any single individual.\n\nAnother example is Ireland, where the president holds a largely ceremonial role, with real executive power vested in the Taoiseach (prime minister).\n\nIn countries like Japan, the Emperor has no governing power, and the prime minister also operates in a system where much of the decision-making is consensus-driven and influenced by various political actors and institutions.\n\nOverall, in comparing nations, the specific system of governance and distribution of powers dictates the influence held by prime ministers or presidents. Switzerland stands out in this regard due to the unique structure of its federal executive council.",
